9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 112, L.D. 179, “An Act to Amend the
10 Maine Bail Code to Eliminate the Class E Crime of Violation of Condition of Release”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'Resolve, to Study the Feasibility of Repealing the Class E Crime of Violation of
13 Condition of Release'
14 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
15 'Preamble. Whereas, between 8,500 and 9,500 Class E violations of conditions of
16 release have been charged across the State in each of the last 5 years; and
17 Whereas, the Legislature observes a need to maintain a strong coordinated
18 community response to bail violations that impact victim safety; and
19 Whereas, eliminating the Class E crime of violation of condition of release and
20 developing alternative mechanisms to maintain an equivalent ability to address bail
21 violations in such cases will require input and collaboration from several stakeholders;
22 now, therefore, be it
23 Sec. 1. Administrative Office of Courts to convene working group.
24 Resolved: That the Administrative Office of the Courts shall convene a working group
25 of stakeholders to study the feasibility of removing the Class E crime of violation of
26 condition of release and, if appropriate, study alternative mechanisms to replace the Class
27 E crime of violation of condition of release that aligns with the purpose and intent of the
28 Maine Bail Code.
29 Sec. 2. Working group membership. Resolved: That the working group under
30 section 1 must include, at a minimum, the following members:
31 1. The State Court Administrator of the Administrative Office of the Courts or the
32 administrator's designee;
33 2. One or more representatives of the judicial branch with expertise in the Maine Bail
34 Code and criminal court process and database management;
Page 1 - 132LR0586(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 112, L.D. 179
1 3. A representative of the Department of Public Safety, Bureau of State Police, State
2 Bureau of Identification with expertise in state and federal law enforcement databases;
3 4. A representative of a statewide association representing chiefs of police;
4 5. A representative of a statewide association representing sheriffs;
5 6. A representative of the Department of Public Safety, Bureau of State Police;
6 7. A representative of a statewide organization with expertise in the pretrial monitoring
7 of individuals charged with crimes;
8 8. A representative of a statewide association of prosecutors;
9 9. A representative of a statewide association of criminal defense lawyers;
10 10. A representative of the Maine Commission on Public Defense Services;
11 11. A representative of a statewide organization of domestic violence service
12 providers;
13 12. A representative of a statewide organization of sexual assault victim support
14 service providers; and
15 13. A representative of a statewide organization advocating for civil liberties.
16 The working group may invite the participation of additional members as necessary to
17 carry out the purposes of the study and may consult with any individual or organization
18 considered appropriate by the working group.
19 Sec. 3. Duties of working group. Resolved: That the working group under
20 section 1 shall study the feasibility of repealing the Class E crime of violation of condition
21 of release and shall consider and address, at a minimum, the following related matters:
22 1. How to maintain a response to violations of bail that implicate victim safety that is
23 equivalent to the response under current law;
24 2. Whether there are case types for which violations of conditions of release should be
25 addressed in a specialized way, including, but not limited to, cases involving domestic
26 violence and sexual assault;
27 3. Whether protective orders may be used as an alternative mechanism for crimes
28 between family members;
29 4. How to ensure judicial officers can still access and consider information about prior
30 compliance with conditions of release in making determinations about current conditions
31 of release;
32 5. How to address a motion to revoke bail when the violation of a condition of release
33 occurred in a different county than the county in which the underlying case is charged;
34 6. How to address a violation of conditions of release that occurs prior to the State's
35 having filed the necessary complaint with the court;
36 7. How to address the current use of violations of conditions of release as sanctions
37 for those participating in Maine's treatment courts;
38 8. Whether there are any other modifications to the Maine Bail Code needed to
39 implement the repeal of the Class E crime of violation of condition of release;
Page 2 - 132LR0586(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 112, L.D. 179
1 9. How to address post-conviction bail violations;
2 10. Estimated costs for implementation of the recommendations; and
3 11. A reasonable time frame for implementation.
4 Sec. 4. Report. Resolved: That, by January 1, 2026, the Administrative Office of
5 the Courts shall submit a report containing the findings and recommendations of the
6 working group under section 1, including proposed legislation, to the Joint Standing
7 Committee on Criminal Justice and Public Safety. The committee may submit legislation
8 based on the report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
9 Sec. 5. Appropriations and allocations. Resolved: That the following
10 appropriations and allocations are made.
11 JUDICIAL DEPARTMENT
12 Courts - Supreme, Superior and District 0063
13 Initiative: Establishes one Criminal Process Specialist position and provides funding for
14 related All Other costs.
